{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_dillon_ver01/data/sn85053223/00517178469/1949042801/0806.xml":{"full_text":"XI HaaraAN \u2018AIXX BWOTOA\nCAMAS HOT SPRINGS\nEXCHANGE\nEdna B. Gannaway, Editor\nA weekly newspaper published\nevery Thursday at Camas, Montana\nEntered at the post oflice at Hot\nSprings, Montana, under the act\nof Congress, March 5, 1879\nSubscription prices 1 year S3M\n6 Months 91.90\nDorothy Von Segen, Hot Springs\nRepresentative, can be contacted at\nthe drug store every morning ex-,\ncept Sunday.\n1949\nEDITORIALS...\nIf you have news or want to know\nabout advertising, you may leave\nwith Mrs Dorothy VonSegen in the\nmorning hours at the Hot Springs\ndrug store. In the afternoon she\ncan be reached in her home, either\nin person or by telephone. Please\ndo not telephone her at the drug\nstore as her time there belongs to\nthe business, but you may leave any\nnews or advertising with her there.\nIn others sections in this paper\nyou will find at least three notices\ncalling attention to the Cancer\nDrive\u2014Public service stuff so it is\nbilled. I' i.s not news\u2014 unless you\ninterpret it bad news. People are get\nting tired of being asked for a\nhand-out every time they turn a\nround. The newspapers are clutter\ned with the calls for publicity. If we\ncould print all the material we are\nrequested to print, we would have a\npaper every week as large as a big\ndaily. We have lost our sympa\u2019hy\nwith all th s \"gimme, gimme, gim\nme\". If Uncle Sam can donate Bil\nlions, send our young men to Europe\nto help those run down nations fur\nther their imperialism, then we\nthink this same Uncle Sam should\ndo a little figuring. Why not budget\nan amount equal to taking care of\nthe research work for cancer, polio,\nheart disease. ctc. -Then all would\npay for it and not the few who al\nways dig up. Also this would be wise\nto sec *hat children grow up with\nstrong bodies and that they do not\ndie of heart disease or cancer before\nthey are old enough to shoulder a\ngun. For just as sure as we are sit\nting, pounding away at this linotype\nour joining in an alliance with west\nIhe RIGHT-Way\nLAUNDRY\nWILL CALL TO PICK UP BUNDLES\nOF CLOTHES WEIGHING 9 Lbs.\nAND MORE.\nHOURS* 8 A.M. lo 7 P.M.\nGive Your Car\nTHAT\nNEW LOOK\nWITH A COMPLETE KEFINISH JOB\nSEE\nHarrison Body Shop\nONE MILE EAST OF BIG RED BARN ON HIGHWAY 28\nUSED\nTRUCKS\n10-48 K-2 INTERNATIONAL PICK-UP \u2014LIKE NEW\n1936 CHEVROLET PICK-UP\n1946 1' _\u2022 TON KS-5 INTEERNATIONAL\n1941 l'i; TON K-5 INT\u2014GOOD FARM TRUCK\nTractors\nFARMALLS CUBS, SUPER \"A\" \u201cC\u2019s\"\nMcCORMICK DEERING W-6 INT. TD-6 CRAWLER\nIJYRR OFFSET DISCS GRAIN DRILL\nFEED GRINDER HAMMER MILL\nDAIRY EQUIPMENT REFRIGERATION\nPARTS and ACCESSORIES\nn. B. OWEN\nInternational Harvester Dealer\n\"N- TB, PI.-\" INS MONTANA\nem Europe, we are always going to 1\nbe at war, one which we believe has\nalready had its beginning \u2014Those\ncountries will be too cock-sure now\nthat we will furnish the money and\nmuch of the army that will be used\nto imperialize weaker colonies' and\nweaker peoples; while if England\ngets a little short on money to keep\ntheir flgurheads in laziness and roll\n,ing in money, she will Just ship a\n(load of the arms we have supplied\nher, to Russa; and there are other\nnations there who will decide, If the\nonce big girl can get away with It,\nwhy not they. England*has been ac\ncused of doing this thing. Now Italy\nwants her lost colonies. Shall we\nhelp her?? Why should she have\nthem, she went in without provo\ncation and massacred those helpless\nless Ethopians? Should she not be\npunished?\nWe fear if we go In to fight Wes\ntern Europe's battles, some of which\nare always raging, it will be the end\nof Democracy in the United States,\nand we may even live to see It.\nFor the first time we have refused\na donation to these \"gimme\u201d hand\nouts. We have already given space\nto 28 'A inches for cancer, which at\nour newspaper rate would be over\n$7.00, We think it enouh. The public\nfails to see that the newspaper that\npublicizes these events is doing just\nas much as tho it gave the cash. The\nnewspaper is our way of making a\nliving and when we give space it\nmust be considered of some value.\nECONOMIC HIGHLIGHTS\u2014\n\u2014From Industrial News Bureau,\niWe do not care a lot for this po\npagandy sheet, \u2014it is all for the big\nbov, but there are facts so evident\noccasionally, that we feel we must\nall give heed and thus we want to\nput them before the public).\nThe attention of many members\nof Congress seems to be wavering\nfrom Mr Truman\u2019s long-range leg\nislative program, and turning to the\n\u25a0immediate problem of just what\ncurrent declines in prices, employ\nment and business activity mean.\nSome of the drop can be attri\nbuted to seasonal factors. But that\ndoesn't account for all of it by quite\na ways. Congress wants to get a\nclearer idea of what is going on be\nfore it does much law making.\nThe House-Senate Committee re\ncently called in a number of lead\ning economists and asked for their\nopinions and advice. As was to be\nexpected, there were many differ\nences. But the majority of these ex-\nTHE CAMAS HflT SPRINGS EXCHANGE, HflfT ggAglft UfVrt/WA\nperts were .agreed that we havei\npassed the peak of Inflation ft thatj\nHowever, there was little talk to\na leveling off period is now at hand,\nthe effect that a severe recession is\nimminent.\nOne of them, representing a large\nlife insurance company, anticipat\ned a long period of good times, tho\nhe added that the buyers\u2019 market Is\nback and the consumer will have to\nbe Induced to buy. Another, from a\npublishing house which issues mag\nazines dealing with industrial ques\ntions, said that he doesn\u2019t fear a ser\nlous downturn is coming, and warn\ned against raising taxes. The econ\nomist for a steel company argued\nthat a big backlog of demand, left\nover from the war days, is still in\nevidence and was optimistic as to\nthe future. A pessimistic note was\nstruck by the economist from a nat\nional research organization, who\nwas none too sure that we have an\neasy road ahead.\nThe point on which most agreed\nwas that there should be no tax in\ncreases, either on business, or on\nindividuals. The reason: these bur\ndens, they think, might prove to be\nsufficient to turn a moderate and\ntemporary decline in business ac\ntivities into a real recession. The\nPresident has said that nothing\nthat has happened has changed his\nview on the tax problem, and Con\ngress should approve his proposal\nfor raising $4,000,000,000 through\nnew taxes. But there are many\ngrave doubts among members of\nboth parties.\nSentiment :s increasing for mak\nling up possible budget deficits by re\niducing the cos\u2019 of government. The\nHoover Commission reports, which\nhave been issued so far, have shown\nI up serious waste which could be el\niminated without touching any es\nsential function. Duplication o. bu\nj reaus, archaic procedures, the a\nbuse of patronage\u2014these are old\nI vices which the Commission hopes\nmay be cured. Mr Hoover\u2019s idea is\nthat the President should have far\nI greater direct powers over the ma-\nI chinery of the government. It is not\nlikely that all of the recommenda\ntions will b? approved. But a start\nwill be made.\nI\nIn The District Court of the Fourth\nJudicial District of the State of\nMontana, In and for the County\nof Sanders\no\nIN THE MATTER OF THE ESTATE\nOF JOSEPH GAGNON, DECEASED\n1 ORDER TO SHOW CAUSE\nOliver Lightner, the executor of\nthe estate of Joseph Gagnon, de\nj ceased, having filed his petition\nherein praying for an order to sell\n:at private sale the real property\nbelonging to said estate for the rea\u2019\nsons and purposes therein set forth.\nIT IS THEREFORE ORDERED\nthat all persons interested in the\nestate of said deceased appear be\n-1 fore the said Court on Monday, the\n16th day of May, 1949, at the hour\nof ten o\u2019clock a m. of said day at\nthe Court Room of said Court in\nThompson Falls, Montana, to show\ncause why an order should not be\ngranted to the said executor to sell\na* private sale all of the property\nbelonging to said estate and which\nis described as follows, to-wit;\nLot 4 of block 13 of the townsite\nof Pincville in the Town of Hot\nSprings, Sanders County, Montana.\nIt is further ordered that this Or\nder be published in the Camas Hot\nSprings Exchange, a weekly news\npaper ptinted and published at\nCamas, Montana, for at least two\nweeks before said day of hearing.\nI Done in Open Court this\n\u25a026th day of 1949.\nC. E. Comer, Judge\nApril 28. May 5-12, 1949\nUncle Sam Says\nYou American citisena who have\nbeen looking for an opportunity to\nlake tome aggressive action which will\nexpress faith in your country are now\nbeing given that chance. It is partici\npation in the U. S. Saving* Bond* Divi\n\u2022inn'* \u201cSpring Opportunity Drive\u201d\nwhich open* May 16. Through thi*\ndrive you can help in the preservation\nof a prosperous economy in your land\nand show the world that Americans,\nmen and women, still have that spark\nwhich has led the country to \u201caccom\nplish the impossible\u201d. Volunteer work\ners are needed to help Hi this greet\ndrive and this is your opportunity to\nprove that you have the courage to\nprotect the freedoms that are our*.\nYour community, your county, your\natnle, and your country needs your\nhelp. Volunteer today.\nVM. Treason Digsrtusal\nThe following articles are offered,\nFOR SALE\n1-Large Oil Burning Heater to\nGood Shape\n1*- Bath Tubs\u2014 Used,\n12- Kitchen Chairs, Heavy Duty\nType.\n3 Mirrors\nArticles are in storage at new\nBath House.\np. A. Roulller, Mgr\nCAMAS HOT SPRINGS\ni\\yah Grange\nMaster Muster Crouch called the\nmeeting of Nyah Grange to order on\nthe regular meeting night, April 20\nwith 28 members and one visitor pre\nsent from Little Bitter Root Grange.\nThree new members wer? voted on\nfavorably for membership\u2014Mrs Bes\nse Madsen, Duane Allen and Glen\nJohnson.\nL. O. Thomas, chairman of the\nbuilding committee gave a report\non the hall, saying that since the\nspring work had begun, Tuesday,\nBJWHTE\nPRICES\nEFFECTIVE\nAPRIL 29, 30, MAY 2\nNATIONAL\nIghnghnghng1 ghnghnghng\nGerber's\nDRY CEREALS\nCEREAL, OATMEAL, BARLEY\n8-Oz. Pkg 19c\nBest fir @OOO3\nCream qa.\nOF WHEAT 30c\nKARO\nRed Label Corn Syrup\nFor Baby Feeding\n1 Vz-Lb. Jar 23c\nSEGO Canned\nMILK\nFor Baby Feeding\n4 Tall Tins 54c\nPABLUM\n18-Oz. Pkg 45c\nJohnson's\nBABY POWDER\nLarge 49c\nJohnson's\nBABY OIL\n6-Oz 49c\nJohnson's\nBABY CREAM\nLarge 49c\nBABYSOAP\nEach 25c\nghnghnghng\nRED W H 1T E\nFriday and Saturday evenings on\nthe hall.\nHome Economic Chairman Fran\nces Oslavskl reported the grange\nbake sale and bazaar a success.\nThe lecturer\u2019s program was in\ncharge of the Grace Sisters\u2014Mary\nCrouch, Rae Thomas and Rhoda\nSmllka. Articles were read and a\ngame was played\u2014What Who with\nand Where which was enjoyed byi\naU.\nOrange meeting nights were vot\ned to be changed from the Ist &3rd\nFriday nights of each month, at the\nnew grange hall. The next meeting\nwill be May 6.\nThe meeting was adjourned and\nlunch was served by Melvle Johnson.\nFOR SALE\u20144S Acres, See any day\nexcept Saturday. F. C. Lee, Loneptoe\n28, May 5-i2p\nFOR SALE\u2014WeII Drill ft Plenty\nof Casing. H. Shreeve, Phone 3937\n507 South 3rd St, Missoula. 7-5 p\nFOR SALE\u20144 Lots to Mountain\nView Addition, Price SIAM, Frances\nHooper, Warner Apartments, Hot\nSprings. 21-28, May 5.\nThis week Baby takes the spotlight at all Red White stores. Now is the\ntime to stock up, on healthful energy-giving body-building baby foods.\nScientifically tested, baby f\u00ab\u00abis help baby grow strong and sturdy. Come\nto Red Sc White today and get baby foods at low prices for YOUR baby!\nT <T)IIHllT At What Your Dol\nXJ XJ JV lar Will Buy Today!\ne\nDC A f LIEC Red White a No. 2 2 l aa\nRMvIIm Y. C. Slic